function combatFocus() {
    let method = [
        `TDM - The typical - kill all the enemies before they kill all the good guys style.`,
        `Guardian - The fight is focused on a VIP. Ex: Typical Boss (VIP) with supporting minions; Escort, PCs protect a NPC ally (VIP) while they do something or go somewhere; Reverse Escort, NPC allies act to support the PCs, or a PC focused escort mission.`,
        `CTF - Fight over an inanimate McGuffin, like a magic rune or bag of gold. Ex: Once the party defeats the warlord, her underlings will try to grab the body and escape to resurrect her; Try to steal a magic gem that’s guarded by a horde of eternally reanimating skeletons; The party reaches a powerful artifact at the same time as a rival adventuring party; having an objective can force battles to happen in circumstances that aren’t ideal to either side. Can lead to chases and clever uses of non-damaging combat abilities.`,
        `COTH - Seek to control a location. This location can start under the control of either faction or start as initially neutral depending on circumstance, and each situation leads to a very different type of encounter. If the location is initially neutral, this functions like a Capture the Flag. Ex: Taking a bridge. One side wants to hold it so that it can be destroyed, another side wants to hold it so that an approaching army can cross. A ‘defensive’ King of the Hill might involve the PCs holding a specific door against enemies that want to burst in and assassinate whoever’s inside. An ‘offensive’ King of the Hill might involve the PCs trying to remain inside a ritual circle to disrupt the summoning of a dark god.`,
        `TD - Wave Defense- Send enemies in waves so that the party doesn't get overwhelmed and to make a combat last more than the traditional three round length. Ex: The party is defending a wall breach against attacking soldiers, or a holy gate against a horde of demons. The enemy can’t attack all at once due to the size of the gap, so they come in waves. Defeat a certain number of enemies, hold out for a certain amount of time, or prevent them from reaching a certain point in order to achieve victory.`,
        `FFA - Survival over body count. The existence of multiple warring factions within a dungeon. If any faction wins decisively, it makes the PCs lives much harder, so it falls the the PCs to ensure that any victory is pyrrhic. EX: An otherwise normal battle is interrupted by a wandering monster looking for an easy meal; A Big Bad’s underling sees the climactic battle with the PCs as the perfect opportunity to betray their boss an eliminate both groups in one fell swoop.`,
    ]
    document.getElementById("Method").innerHTML = searchArray(method);
};

